#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn how to use include directives to modularize your Spack YAML "
"configuration files for better organization and reusability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:13
msgid "Include Settings (include.yaml)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:15
msgid ""
"Spack allows you to include configuration files through ``include.yaml``, or "
"in the ``include:`` section in an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:18
msgid "Local files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:20
msgid ""
"You can include a single configuration file or an entire configuration "
"*scope* like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:22
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- /path/to/a/required/config.yaml\n"
"- path: /path/to/$os/$target/config\n"
"  optional: true\n"
"- path: /path/to/os-specific/config-dir\n"
"  when: os == \"ventura\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:31
msgid ""
"Included paths may be absolute, relative (to the configuration file), or "
"they can be specified as URLs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:33
msgid ""
"``optional``: Spack will raise an error when an included configuration file "
"does not exist, *unless* it is explicitly made ``optional: true``, like the "
"second path above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:34
msgid ""
"``when``: Configuration scopes can also be included *conditionally* with "
"``when``. ``when:`` conditions are evaluated as described for :ref:`Spec "
"List References <spec-list-references>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:38
msgid ""
"The same conditions and variables in :ref:`Spec List References <spec-list-"
"references>` can be used for conditional activation in the ``when`` clauses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:41
msgid "Remote file URLs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:43
msgid ""
"Only the ``file``, ``ftp``, ``http``, and ``https`` protocols (or schemes) "
"are supported for remote file URLs. Spack-specific, environment, and user "
"path variables can be used. (See :ref:`config-file-variables` for more "
"information.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:47
msgid "A ``sha256`` is required and must be specified as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:49
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- path: https://github.com/path/to/raw/config/config.yaml\n"
"  sha256: 26e871804a92cd07bb3d611b31b4156ae93d35b6a6d6e0ef3a67871fcb1d258b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:55
msgid ""
"The ``config.yaml`` file would be cached locally to a special include "
"location and its contents included in Spack's configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:59
msgid ""
"Remote file URLs must link to the **raw** form of the file's contents (e.g., "
"`GitHub <https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/working-with-files/using-"
"files/viewing-and-understanding-files#viewing-or-copying-the-raw-file-"
"content>`_ or `GitLab <https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/api/repository_files."
"html#get-raw-file-from-repository>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:62
msgid "``git`` repository files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:64
msgid ""
"You can also include configuration files from a ``git`` repository. The "
"`branch`, `commit`, or `tag` to be checked out is required. A list of "
"relative paths in which to find the configuration files is also required. "
"Inclusion of the repository (and its paths) can be optional or conditional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:69
msgid ""
"For example, suppose we only want to include the ``config.yaml`` and "
"``packages.yaml`` files from the `spack/spack-configs <https://github.com/"
"spack/spack-configs>`_ repository's ``USC/config`` directory when using the "
"``centos7`` operating system. We would then configure the ``include.yaml`` "
"file as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:72
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- git: https://github.com/spack/spack-configs\n"
"  branch: main\n"
"  when: os == \"centos7\"\n"
"  paths:\n"
"  - USC/config/config.yaml\n"
"  - USC/config/packages.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:82
msgid ""
"If the condition is satisfied, then the ``main`` branch of the repository "
"will be cloned and the settings for the two files integrated into Spack's "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:84
msgid "``git:``, ``branch:``, ``commit:``, and ``tag:`` attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:88
msgid "Precedence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:90
msgid ""
"Using ``include:`` adds the included files as a configuration scope *below* "
"the including file. This is so that you can override settings from files you "
"include. If you want one file to take precedence over another, you can put "
"the include with higher precedence earlier in the list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:94
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- /path/to/higher/precedence/scope/\n"
"- /path/to/middle/precedence/scope/\n"
"- git: https://github.com/org/git-repo-scope\n"
"  commit: 95c59784bd02ea248bf905d79d063df38e087b19"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:103
msgid "``prefer_modify``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:105
msgid ""
"When you use commands like ``spack compiler find``, ``spack external find``, "
"``spack config edit`` or ``spack config add``, they modify the topmost "
"writable scope in the current configuration. Scopes can tell Spack to prefer "
"to edit their included scopes instead, using ``prefer_modify``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:108
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- name: \"preferred\"\n"
"  path: /path/to/scope/we/want-to-write\n"
"  prefer_modify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:115
msgid ""
"Now, if the including scope is the highest precedence scope and would "
"otherwise be selected automatically by one fo these commands, they will "
"instead prefer to edit ``preferred``. The including scope can still be "
"modified by using the ``--scope`` argument (e.g., ``spack compiler find --"
"scope NAME``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:120
msgid ""
"Recursive includes are not currently processed in a breadth-first manner, so "
"the value of a configuration option that is altered by multiple included "
"files may not be what you expect. This will be addressed in a future update."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:123
msgid "The ``prefer_modify:`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:126
msgid "Overriding local paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:128
msgid ""
"Optionally, you can enable a local path to be overridden by an environment "
"variable using ``path_override_env_var:``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:130
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- path_override_env_var: SPECIAL_CONFIG_PATH\n"
"  path: /path/to/special/config.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:136
msgid ""
"Here, If ``SPECIAL_CONFIG_PATH`` is set, its value will be used as the path. "
"If not, Spack will instead use the ``path:`` specified in configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:141
msgid ""
"``path_override_env_var:`` is currently only supported for ``path:`` "
"includes, not ``git:`` includes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:143
msgid "The ``path_override_env_var:`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:147
msgid "Named configuration scopes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:149
msgid ""
"By default, the included scope names are is constructed by appending ``:`` "
"and the included scope's basename to the parent scope name. For example, "
"Spack's own ``defaults`` scope includes a ``base`` scope and a platform-"
"specific scope::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:152
msgid ""
"> spack config scopes -p\n"
"Scope            Path\n"
"command_line\n"
"spack            /home/username/spack/etc/spack/\n"
"user             /home/username/.spack/\n"
"site             /home/username/spack/etc/spack/site/\n"
"defaults         /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/\n"
"defaults:darwin  /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/darwin/\n"
"defaults:base    /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/base/\n"
"_builtin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:163
msgid ""
"You can see ``defaults`` and the included ``defaults:base`` and ``defaults:"
"darwin`` scopes here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:165
msgid ""
"If you want to define your own name for an included scope, you can supply an "
"optional ``name:`` argument when you include it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:167
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:\n"
"  - path: foo\n"
"    name: myscope"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:174
msgid "You can see the ``myscope`` name when we activate this environment::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:176
msgid ""
"> spack -e ./env config scopes -p\n"
"Scope                    Path\n"
"command_line\n"
"env:/home/username/env   /home/username/env/spack.yaml/\n"
"myscope                  /home/username/env/foo/\n"
"spack                    /home/username/spack/etc/spack/\n"
"user                     /home/username/.spack/\n"
"site                     /home/username/spack/etc/spack/site/\n"
"defaults                 /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/\n"
"defaults:darwin          /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/darwin/\n"
"defaults:base            /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/base/\n"
"_builtin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:189
msgid ""
"You can now use the argument ``myscope`` to refer to this, for example with "
"``spack config --scope myscope add ...``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:192
msgid "Built-in configuration scopes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:194
msgid ""
"The default ``user``, ``system``, and ``site`` scopes are defined using "
"``include:`` in ``$spack/etc/spack/include.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:196
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"  # user configuration scope\n"
"  - name: \"user\"\n"
"    path_override_env_var: SPACK_USER_CONFIG_PATH\n"
"    path: \"~/.spack\"\n"
"    optional: true\n"
"    prefer_modify: true\n"
"    when: '\"SPACK_DISABLE_LOCAL_CONFIG\" not in env'\n"
"\n"
"  # site configuration scope\n"
"  - name: \"site\"\n"
"    path: \"$spack/etc/spack/site\"\n"
"    optional: true\n"
"\n"
"  # system configuration scope\n"
"  - name: \"system\"\n"
"    path_override_env_var: SPACK_SYSTEM_CONFIG_PATH\n"
"    path: \"/etc/spack\"\n"
"    optional: true\n"
"    when: '\"SPACK_DISABLE_LOCAL_CONFIG\" not in env'\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:199
msgid ""
"You can see that all three of these scopes are given meaningful names, and "
"all three are ``optional``, i.e., they'll be ignored if their directories do "
"not exist. The ``user`` and ``system`` scopes can also be disabled by "
"setting ``SPACK_DISABLE_LOCAL_CONFIG``. Finally, the ``user`` scope can be "
"overridden with a path in ``SPACK_USER_CONFIG_PATH`` if it is set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:204
msgid "Overriding scopes by name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:206
msgid ""
"Configuration scopes have unique names. This means that you can use the "
"``name:`` attribute to *replace* a builtin scope. If you supply an "
"environment like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:210
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:\n"
"  - path: foo\n"
"    name: user"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:217
msgid ""
"The newly included ``user`` scope will *completely* override the builtin "
"``user`` scope::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:219
msgid ""
"> spack -e ~/env config scopes -p\n"
"Scope                    Path\n"
"command_line\n"
"env:/home/username/env   /home/username/env/spack.yaml/\n"
"user                     /home/username/env/foo/\n"
"spack                    /home/username/spack/etc/spack/\n"
"site                     /home/username/spack/etc/spack/site/\n"
"defaults                 /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/\n"
"defaults:darwin          /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/darwin/\n"
"defaults:base            /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/base/\n"
"_builtin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:233
msgid ""
"Using ``name:`` to override the ``defaults`` scope can have *very* "
"unexpected consequences and is not advised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:235
msgid "The ``name:`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:239
msgid "Overriding built-in scopes with ``include::``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:241
msgid ""
"In some cases, you may want to override *all* of the built-in configuration "
"scopes. The ``user`` and ``system`` scopes depend on the user and the "
"machine on which Spack is running, and they can end up bringing in "
"unexpected configuration settings in surprising ways."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:244
msgid ""
"If you want to eliminate them completely from an environment, you can write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:246
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:: []"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:251
msgid ""
"This overrides all scopes except the ``defaults`` that Spack needs in order "
"to function. You can see that ``spack``, ``user``, and ``site`` are "
"overridden::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:254
msgid ""
"> spack -e ~/env config scopes -vp\n"
"Scope                    Type          Status    Path\n"
"command_line             internal      active\n"
"env:/home/username/env   env,path      active    /home/username/env/spack."
"yaml/\n"
"spack                    path          override  /home/username/spack/etc/"
"spack/\n"
"user                     include,path  override  /home/username/.spack/\n"
"site                     include,path  override  /home/username/spack/etc/"
"spack/site/\n"
"defaults                 path          active    /home/username/spack/etc/"
"spack/defaults/\n"
"defaults:darwin          include,path  active    /home/username/spack/etc/"
"spack/defaults/darwin/\n"
"defaults:base            include,path  active    /home/username/spack/etc/"
"spack/defaults/base/\n"
"_builtin                 internal      active"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:266
msgid ""
"And if you run ``spack config blame``, the settings from these scopes will "
"no longer show up. ``defaults`` are not overridden as they are needed by "
"Spack to function. This allows you to create completely isolated "
"environments that do not bring in external settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../include_yaml.rst:270
msgid "``include::`` with two colons for overriding."
msgstr ""
